# Spec-Driven Development

When building features with AI agents, write a **spec** before code. Specs eliminate guesswork and give agents a clear contract.

## When to Use

- Starting a new feature (3+ files, 30+ min)
- Agent keeps guessing wrong approach
- Need to pause, review, or hand off mid-feature

## Spec Structure

```markdown
# Feature Name
## Why — Problem being solved
## What — Concrete deliverable
## Constraints — Must / Must Not / Out of Scope
## Current State — Relevant files, patterns
## Tasks — T1, T2... each with What, Files, Verify
## Validation — End-to-end checks
```

## Workflow

1. **Generate spec** — Use `.ai/templates/spec.md`, save to `.ai/specs/<feature-slug>.md`
2. **Review & refine** — Ensure decisions are yours
3. **Execute one task** — Fresh session: "Read .ai/specs/X.md and implement T1"
4. **Verify, review, commit** — Run verify step, human review, commit
5. **Repeat** for each task

## Task Rules

- **Fresh context per task** — New session avoids context rot
- **Small tasks** — <3 files, <30 min each
- **Verify mandatory** — Every task needs: `command` or `Manual: [specific check]`

## Rules vs Specs

| Rules (.cursor/rules) | Specs (.ai/specs) |
|----------------------|-------------------|
| Coding standards, personas | Feature contracts, tasks |
| Always/glob-triggered | Per-feature, on demand |
| "How to write code" | "What to build, what not to build" |
